The purpose of this lab is to get you familiar with fitting classification models in R.

Simulating data:

We will simulate something like the weight vs.age data from a cubic function and add some noise and then apply a few methods.

  1. Simulate a multivariate (3 variables) predictor with 3 classes using the following.
nsamp <- 100 
SMat <- matrix(c(1.0, 0.6, 0.3, 0.4, 1.0, 0.7, 0.1, 0.1, 1.0), nrow=3, ncol=3) 
datmat1 <- mvrnorm(n = nsamp, mu = rep(-1.0, 3), Sigma = SMat) 
datmat2 <- mvrnorm(n = nsamp, mu = rep(1.0, 3), Sigma = SMat) 
datmat3 <- mvrnorm(n = nsamp, mu = c(0.0,0.5,-1.0), Sigma = SMat)
  1. Stack datamat1, datamat2, and datamat3 to generate a single 300x3 matrix called datamat.
datamat <- rbind(datmat1, datmat2, datmat3)
dim(datamat)
## [1] 300   3
  1. Generate a groups factor such that the first 100 data points are labeled outcome1, the second 100 outcome2, and the third 100 outcome3.
groups <- factor(c(rep("outcome1", nsamp), rep("outcome2", nsamp), rep("outcome3", nsamp)))
  1. Combine groups and datamat into a data frame called dat. Give the dataframe column names groups, predictor1, predictor2, predictor3.
dat <- data.frame(
  groups=groups,
  datamat
)

names(dat) <- c("groups", "predictor1", "predictor2", "predictor3")
  1. Make pairwise plots of the predictors in the data using the command pairs.
pairs(dat)

  1. Re-do the scatterplot so that get each data-point is color coded by groups using the col argument.
pairs(dat, col=1+as.numeric(dat$groups))

  1. Use it to plot the data in 3D using scatterplot3d. Color-code the points by group.
s3d <- scatterplot3d(dat$predictor1, dat$predictor2, dat$predictor3, xlab="Predictor 1", ylab="Predictor 2", zlab="Predictor 3", pch=16, color=1+as.numeric(dat$groups), main="3D Scatterplot")

legend(s3d$xyz.convert(3.5, 2,3), levels(dat$groups), col = 2:4, pch=16)

  1. Simulate a new set of test data (call it test_dat) with the same settings and the same number of observations. Use set.seed(15) instead.
set.seed(15)

nsamp <- 100 
SMat <- matrix(c(1.0, 0.6, 0.3, 0.4, 1.0, 0.7, 0.1, 0.1, 1.0), nrow=3, ncol=3) 
datmat1b <- mvrnorm(n = nsamp, mu = rep(-1.0, 3), Sigma = SMat) 
datmat2b <- mvrnorm(n = nsamp, mu = rep(1.0, 3), Sigma = SMat) 
datmat3b <- mvrnorm(n = nsamp, mu = c(0.0,0.5,-1.0), Sigma = SMat) 

datmatb <- rbind(datmat1b, datmat2b, datmat3b)
test_dat <- data.frame(groups, datmatb)
names(test_dat) <- c("groups", "predictor1", "predictor2", "predictor3")

Logistic Regression

  1. Subset the dataset so that there are only the groups: outcome1 and outcome2. Call the new data dat2. You should run dat2 <- droplevels(dat2) to remove the unused level from the factor. Otherwise R will still think you have a outcome3 group.
dat2 <- subset(dat, subset=groups %in% c("outcome1", "outcome2"))
dat2 <- droplevels(dat2)
levels(dat2$groups)
## [1] "outcome1" "outcome2"
  1. Fit a logistic regression with groups as the outcome/response variable and all 3 predictors (additive).
glm1 <- glm(groups ~ predictor1 + predictor2 + predictor3, family=binomial(), data=dat2)
# this is the same thing
#glm1 <- glm(groups ~ ., family=binomial(), data=dat2)
  1. Run summary on your model.
summary(glm1)

  1. Subset test dataset test_dat so that it only has observations from outcome1 and outcome2. Using the logistic regression model to predict the probability each observation in this filtered test dataset.
test_dat_subset <- subset(test_dat, subset=groups != "outcome3")
test_dat_subset$groups <- droplevels(test_dat_subset$groups)
predictions <- predict(glm1, test_dat_subset, type = "response")
  1. Use the ROCit package to fit and plot an ROC curve for this model using the test dataset using the rocit function.
rocit_obj <- rocit(score = predictions, class=test_dat_subset$groups)
plot(rocit_obj)

  1. What is the AUC and its 95% confidence interval (see ciAUC)?
(ci_auc <- ciAUC(rocit_obj))

Linear discriminant analysis

  1. Fit a linear discriminant analysis to the original data with 3 groups.
lda_fit <- lda(groups ~ ., data=dat)
  1. Compare the estimated group means with the values used in the simulation.
lda_fit # outcome1 approx -1, outcome2 approx 1, outcome3 approx 0. output shown below

  1. Examine the 3x3 table of predicted vs.actual observations in the training data.
lda_pred_train <- predict(lda_fit)

table(pred=lda_pred_train$class, true=dat$groups)
##           true
## pred       outcome1 outcome2 outcome3
##   outcome1       78        6       12
##   outcome2        8       89        5
##   outcome3       14        5       83
  1. Calculate prediction accuracy in the training data.
mean(lda_pred_train$class == dat$groups)
## [1] 0.8333333
  1. Examine the 2x2 table of predicted vs.actual observations in the test dataset test_dat.
lda_pred_test <- predict(lda_fit, newdata = test_dat)
table(pred=lda_pred_test$class, true=test_dat$groups)
##           true
## pred       outcome1 outcome2 outcome3
##   outcome1       77        9        9
##   outcome2        4       84        8
##   outcome3       19        7       83
  1. Examine the predictive accuracy in the test dataset test_dat. How different is it?
mean(lda_pred_test$class == test_dat$groups)
## [1] 0.8133333
